{"insight":"A lesson ripens when it can rest","publicTitle":"When Repeating Stops Learning","plainSummary":"Repeating the same truth without new evidence can hide the work we still need to do.","atAGlance":"We can confuse saying it again with seeing it more clearly. A true lesson eventually asks us to gather it, pause it, and test it. Repetition can teach, but it can also protect us from the next honest step.","keyPoints":["Meaning grows when repetition brings a new act or a new check.","Endless rewording can become a way to avoid the harder question.","Ask what new evidence would change, deepen, or retire the lesson."],"match":["restating is not realizing"],"tags":["learning","practice","testing"]}
